post_text:
COVID-19 Prevention Efforts at Athletics are as follows:
1. Athletes wash hands after entering locker room.
2. Athletes will be assigned lockers with empty lockers adjacent, or with locker of sibling adjacent.
3. Athletes must confirm they have no current symptoms, or symptoms within the last 10 days, prior to practice.
4. Athletes will be assigned 1 (one) workout partner for a season.
5. No more than 4 athletes will be allowed in weight room at one time.
6. Full contact drills are limited to two days per week.
7. Balls and equipment will be cleaned/disinfected after each practice.
8. Athletes must wash hands before departing the locker rooms.
9. No loitering allowed in locker rooms.
10. Seating on buses will maximize distance between riders and windows will be opened, weather permitting.

END OF SCHOOL YEAR INFORMATION FOR DIRKS-ANDERSON ELEMENTARY.
Today, students will return school materials including books, computers & chargers, and pick up personal belongings. To maintain social distancing, each class will have a specific time to come to school.
9 a.m. - PreK and 1st grade 9:30 - Kindergarten and 2nd grade 10 a.m. - 3rd grade (last name A-M) 10:30 a.m. - 3rd grade (last Name N-Z) 11 a.m. - 4th grade 11:30 a.m. - 5th grade.
PreK and Kindergarten students will enter through the gate in the staff parking lot and walk to the classroom. All other students will enter through the front door of the school. Thank you for all your help to make this a successful school year, with both at school learning and at home learning.

END OF SCHOOL YEAR INFORMATION FOR FORT DAVIS JUNIOR-SENIOR HIGH SCHOOL. Today, students will return all school materials including books, computers, chargers, calculators, & other electronics and pick up personal belongings. To maintain social distancing, each class will have a specific time to come to the campuses. 9 a.m.- 6th grade; 10 a.m.- 7th grade; 11 a.m.- 8th grade; 1 p.m.- 9th grade; 2 p.m.-10th grade; 3 p.m.- 11th and 12th grade. Junior/Senior High School students will return and pick up material at the distance-learning room exit located in the student parking lot. Seniors will also pick up two community gifts.

For more information call principals Luane Porter at 432-426-4444 or Allison Scott at 432-426-4454. Thank you for your all your help to make this a successful school year, with both at school learning and at home learning.

post_text: We would like to sincerely thank all of our teachers here at Fort Davis ISD for the amazing work you do for our students. You are strong, courageous, determined, knowledgeable, and caring people who work tirelessly to nurture, guide, and educate these growing young minds. You are truly an outstanding group of professional educators who have a great passion for teaching and open your hearts to these young people on a daily basis. We stand in awe daily of all the wonderful things you do! May God bless you and keep you all the days of your life. With sincere gratitude and love, Luane Porter and Allison Scott

If you will be in grades 6-12 next year, and are interested in running for class representative for the student council, please email Mrs. Pittman at spittman@fdisd.com by Thursday, May 7th.

post_text:
What Young Minds are Pondering During Off-Site Instruction!

Junior High student, Michael Haller, has always been curious about the ratios of Froot Loop colors. So last week he decided to sort it out.

He weighed each color (weight in oz) then calculated the percentages. Then he discussed how to compare the ratios too, with so many comparisons you could make!

Blue: 1.4, 6%
Green: 2.85, 13%
Purple: 3.02, 14%
Red: 5.61, 26%
Yellow: 2.94, 13%
Orange: 6.03, 28%

Total weight: 21.85 oz.

Learning enriched through home projects...
Go Indians!

Yearbooks should be ready for pick up around May 18. If you want the book mailed directly to your home address, please let us know and include an additional $3.00 for shipping.

Go Indians!

post_text:
Counseling for Students Available

The outbreak of coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) may be stressful for people. Fear and anxiety about a disease can be overwhelming and cause strong emotions in adults and children. We, at FDISD, are committed to our students' health and well-being.

FDISD has 3 licensed school counselors available to provide counseling services to our students through phone, email, and Zoom (video conferencing with or without video).

Please contact us if you are in need of services.
During school hours:
(432) 426-4454 Dirks Anderson Counselor
(432) 426-4444 FD Junior-Senior High School Counselors
Or via email:
Allison Scott at ascott@fdisd.com
Trava Baker at tbaker@fdisd.com
Luane Porter at slporter@fdisd.com

If you are in immediate distress, contact the suicide hotline at
Call: 800-273-8255 (800-273-TALK)
Chat online: suicidepreventionlifeline.org
La Red Nacional de PrevenciÃ³n del Suicidio: 888-628-9454

If you have an emergency, call 911.

We are Fort Davis Indian Strong!

FDISD will have a school staff parade around town Thursday, March 26 beginning at 6 p.m. Everyone is invited to come out of their homes and wave to us. Or, join along the parade route remembering to keep a safe social distance from one another.

We will roll out at 6 p.m. from the junior high parking lot and begin at the Fort Davis Estates, drive through the Estates and then back to the highway.

Here is the rest of our parade route.
Right on Paisano
Right on Cemetery Dr
Left (east) on Military Dr
Left on Johnson/Compromise
Right on Blackfoot
Left on Highway 17
Right on Cavalry Road
Left on Fort Street
Left on Front Street
Left on Davis Street
Right on Third Street
Right on Highway 17 (State Street)
Right (west) on Court Street
Left on Desert Willow
Ends at high school on Webster Street

See you along the parade route!

TEA posted the following as reminder of what individuals can do to slow the spread of flu and other viruses such as the Coronavirus:
All individuals are encouraged to:

Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.
Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer.
Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.
Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash.
If youâ€™ve not already gotten one, a flu shot is encouraged.

We are going to the Pumpkin Patch today!

All Dirks-Anderson students and staff will travel to
Mandujano Brothers Pumpkin Patch in Cayanosa. We will leave at 8 a.m. and return by 3:45 p.m.
We will eat lunch at the Pumpkin Patch.
Students need to bring: a sack lunch, bottle of water and a hat. Students must wear jeans or pants and closed shoes, no sandals. Students may bring spending money for the gift shop.

It's Goat and Lamb Validation Time!

All FFA and 4H students showing goats and lambs in this year's stock shows need to validate your animals this Sunday, October 27th at the Alpine Show Barn. Goat validation is 1:00pm-2:30pm. Lamb validation is 2:30pm-3:30pm.

For questions, please contact Mayle Chambliss, FFA Advisor, at 432-426-4444.

post_text:
Celebrating National Earth Science Week, our 5th grade students learn about renewable energy resources; the effects of weathering, erosion and deposition; groundwater; rocks and minerals mined in the region; levers and pulleys used in mining; and they get to hike one of the trails to learn first-hand about land formations and the effects of geological
forces at work while visiting CDRI.
